The totes arrived early A.M. on 01/08/06 on trailer 47902. The trailer was parked on the terminal yard until the next driver was dispatched on the load. This driver did a pre-trip inspection and found the trailer leaking. Further inspection identified the leak to most likely be coming from the load   of 6 totes. A clean up team was contracted. They entered the trailer and inspected the totes. They found that a release valve did not function properly.  The temp reached 71 on this day causing the tote to expand and release some of the product. The team identified a small split at the top and botto  m of the leaking tote. There was also 1 other tote found building pressure but the tote had not failed yet. The clean up team released the pressure from the tote before any damage occurred. (Costs entered on this initial report are strictly estimates, not actual costs. The actual costs, when known,   will be entered on a supplemental report.)
column169: The valves did not function properly. Corrective steps should be taken to prevent the faulty valves from being placed into transportation.

column168: A shipment with two 55-gallon drums arrived with one drum leaking.  The person working in the yard notice liquid leaking out of the trailer and had me go outside to inspect.  He brought the trailer to our dock door and the leaking drum was placed upside down in a recovery drum.  There was a small slit in the bottom of the drum (less than an inch long).  I could not identify the cause of the slit.  We weighed the drum that was not leaking (668 lbs) and the drum that was leaking (368 lbs inside of the recovery drum).  Estimated that approximately 25 gallons had leaked out in transit.
column169: It is difficult to make recommendations because it is not apparent as to the cause of the leakage.  I don't know if the drum had a little kink in the bottom before filling and then failed due to the weight?

column168: Univar arrived at the customers site to deliver four drums of Sodium Bisulfite. The customer placed a steel plate on the trailer and dock to transfer the product.  While pulling the product off the trailer the plate slid back and the pallet was balancing on the edge of the truck. The customer then removed a drum from the pallet causing one of the drums to fall. The drum struck the dock and was punctured. The driver grabbed the drum and positioned the drum so no further contents would spill. The driver used Soda Ash to contain the product. The spill was then cleaned up and containerized and will be disposed of to meet federal regulations.
column169: Univar has contacted the customer and has asked them to purchase a dock plate. Univar will deliver future orders with a lift gate to their site until the equipment has been received.

column168: Upon inspection of his trailer the driver noted a small amount of material leaking from the right rear of the trailer.  He immediately called for a spill clean up crew.  Upon arrival, a Site Safety meeting was held with the local Fire Department and emergency management officials, who at which time, a Plan of Action was developed and agreed to. Summitt then donned personal protective equipment and opened the trailer doors. An evaluation was performed utilizing an air meter and the air quality and explosion level of the environment was determined. All levels were within normal limits and 0% levels were determined. Summitt then entered the trailer and evaluated the load and determined that 1 55 steel drum that was banded to a pallet had released approximately half of the volume in the drum. The floor area was saturated with the product. Summitt placed absorbent products on the floor areas and recovered the liquid. A fork lift was requested, received and utilized to remove the packages. All packages were removed and examined for the product and placed onto the plastic next to the trailer. The damaged drum was inspected and it was determined that there was a small hole in the bottom of the drum that appeared to develop from a rubbing action with the pallet. No obvious nails were present on the pallet. The drum was then overpacked into a 95 gallon poly overpack and secured. The pallet was removed and dismantled and placed into a 55 gallon drum. The remaining area was cleaned using absorbent product and industrial agents. The driver then examined the trailer and determined no other product existed. The trailer was reloaded with the poly overpack remaining on the trailer and continuing on to the destination. 1 55 gallon steel DOT approved drum was used in the cleanup. The area was secured and the driver released to his destination.
column169: A suggestion will be made to all shippers to inspect the quality of their drums prior to any shipment.  In addition, all drivers will be reminded to inspect their load prior to leaving the shipper location.

column168: I SLOWED DOWN FOR A PEDESTRIAN, POSITION THE TRUCK ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE ROAD, CONTINUED SOUTH ON BUCKRIDGE, TRAVELING ALONG A STEEP BAR DITCH. I FELT MY FRONT TIRE SLIDE INTO THE BAR DITCH AND THEN THE REAR FOLLOWED. I FELT THE TRUCK TIP TO THE RIGHT. FEARING THE TRUCK ROLLING OVER TO THE RIGHT, I REACTED BY TRYING TO DRIVE THE TRUCK BACK UP TO ROAD BY TURNING THE STEERING WHEEL TO THE LEFT. I GOT THE TRUCK BACK ON THE ROAD AND FELT THE TRUCK REAREND SLIDE BACK AND FORTH. I TRIED TO REGAIN CONTROL BUT WENT OFF THE LEFT SIDE OF THE ROAD AFTER APPLYING THE BRAKES AND SLIDING THROUGH THE BAR DITCH. THE TRUCK THEN ROLLED ONTO THE LEFT SIDE. I COULD HEAR AND SMELL PROPANE LEAKING, I SHUT THE MOTOR OFF AND CLIMBED OUT OF THE TRUCK. I THEN CALLED THE OFFICE. (ERICIA) CALLED DPS AND THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT, THEN THE COMPANY MANAGER WAS CALLED AND HEADED FOR THE SCENE OF THE ACCIDENT. JEFF THE MANGER, CALLED MIKE THE DRIVER TO GET THE INFORMATION ON THE ACCIDENT AND MAKE SURE THE DRIVER WAS OKAY. MIKE TOLD JEFF THE TRUCK WAS LEAKING FUEL BUT HE WAS NOT SURE WHERE. JEFF TOLD MIKE TO KEEP PEOPLE AND VEHICLES WAY FROM THE AREA. WHEN JEFF ARRIVED TO THE FIRE, DPS AND SHERIFFS DEPT. WERE ALL ON THE SCENE AFTER DETERMINING THE LEAK WAS LIQUID, I TRIED TO GET CLOSE ENOUGH TO SEE WHERE THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM. DPS AND WFD PUT ON SAFETY GEAR SO THEY COULD GET CLOSE TO THE TRUCK. I ASKED THEM TO GET THE PRESSURE IN THE TANK AND TO DESCRIBE WHERE THE FUEL WAS COMING FROM. THE DESCRIPTION THEY GAVE WAS DESCRIBING THE 3 1/4 ACME FILL VALVE. IT WAS DETERMINED THE LEAK COULD NOT BE STOPPED. I THEN HAD THE SERVICE MAN TAKE THE DRIVER OF THE TRUCK TO THE HOSPITAL TO BE CHECKED OUT. THEN I CALLED PERS TO MAKE A REPORT OF THE INCIDENT. THEY TOLD ME TO CALL THE STATE AND FEDERAL DEPT. TO MAKE A REPORT WITH THEM. I NOTIFIED THE FEDERAL BUT THE STATE OFFICE WAS CLOSED. DURING THIS TIME THE FIRE DEPT WAS EVACUATING PEOPLE AND SHUTTING OFF ANY SOURCE OF IGNITION. OUR OFFICE WAS CONTACTING A LOCAL HOTEL FOR ROOMS FOR ANYONE WHO WAS EVACUATED AND NEEDED A ROOM. THE RED CROSS WAS SETTING UP TO HELP WHEREVER THEY COULD.  AFTER APPROX. 4 HOURS, A DPS HAZMAT OFFICER CAME UP TO ME WITH AN AIR QUALITY METER. I HAD BINOCULARS AND I WANTED TO SEE A FROST LINE ON THE TRUCK TANK TO DETERMINE HOW MUCH GAS WAS IN THE TANK.  I ASKED HIM HOW CLOSE HE COULD GET ME TO THE TRUCK AND HE WALKED ME UP CLOSE TO THE TRUCK. I COULD THEN SEE THAT THE LEAK WAS A VAPOR LEAK AND IT WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE VAPOR ELIMINATOR I EXPLAINED TO A FIREFIGHTER WHICH VALVE TO SHUT OFF TO STOP THE LEAK. ONCE CLOSED THE LEAK STOPPED. I THEN MET WITH THE HAZMAT OFFICERS. I LET THEM KNOW IT WAS SAFE TO TURN THE TRUCK BACK UP ON ITS WHEELS AFTER I INSPECTED THE TRUCK AND THE PIPING TO BE SURE ALL WAS SAFE. THE HAZMAT HAD US WAIT ANOTHER HALF HOUR TO LET THE AREA AIR OUT BEFORE WE COULD MOVE THE TRUCK. WE THEN CALLED THE TOW TRUCK OUT AND HAD OUR OTHER DRIVER BRING OUT AN EMPTY BOBTAIL TO PUMP OVER THE FUEL.

column168: On 1/24/2006, a leaking drum was discovered during a daily inspection of the Onyx 10-day in-transit storage area located in Tonawanda, NY.  The leak was discovered to be from a drum that contained solvent and paint waste.  The leak was from numerous holes in the side of the drum.  The duration of the leak was less than 24 hours, from the previous days inspection.    The material leaked onto the storage trailer floor and then onto the containment area outside of the trailer.  The leaked material was absorbed with clay oil-dry and placed into a 55-gallon open head drum for final disposal.  The leaking drum was then overpacked in accordance with DOT regulations.

column168: While offloading the trailer at the destination facility, a leak was discovered eminating from a pallet with three 55-gallon drums.  An emergency response crew was immediately called.  Upon arrival to the site, the crew determined that one   55-gallon drum of Epoxy UF paint was leaking due to a pinhole in the body of the drum.  This drum was immediately overpacked in an 85-gallon salvage drum.  The crew then placed granular sorbents down to absorb all the free product on the trailer floor and the asphalt under the trailer.  These were then swept up and placed in a 55-gallon drum for disposal.  The saturated pallet was also cut up and placed in the same 55-gallon drum for disposal.    The other two drums on the pallet were not leaking.  One was severely dented and was also placed into an 85-gallon salvage drum and the other was accepted by the consignee.  From the initial call for an emergency response crew to the final staging of the disposal drums, the time duration was 4.5 hours.

column168: On 1-18-06 at 0735, during a routine pre-operational inspection, Ulrich personnel detected a slight chlorine gas leak in railcar #GATX 44537.  This car had been received into Ulrich’s facility on 1-17-06.  Initial investigation revealed that the leak was originating from under the railcar valve/man-way located on top of the car.  However, due to the car construction, visual verification of the exact location and extent of damage could not be determined.  At 0755 (1-18-06), Ulrich personnel determined that an in-house hazmat response was not feasible, since the exact location of the leak could not be confirmed. Therefore, Occidental Chemical Corporation (OXY) was contacted for   assistance.  OXY dispatched personnel from their Niagara Falls facility and began the process of dispatching Specialty Response Solutions (SRS) hazmat team from Fort Worth, Texas.  At 1000 (1-18-06), Ulrich personnel met with the Terre Haute Fire Department (THFD) to establish a contingency plan in case the incident should escalate.  THFD agreed to implement the following:  (1). Notify surrounding schools of potential for sheltering-in-place of students and faculty; (2). Coordinate with the Terre Haute Transit Authority to provide city buses in case an evacuation was deemed necessary; (3). Briefed the Terre Haute Police Department and (4). Placed department hazmat responders on stand-by for assisting Ulrich personnel if needed.  At 1030 (1-18-06), Ulrich personnel began offloading the railcar, without air padding, into ton containers.  This decreased the overall quantity of chlorine and reduce internal pressure within the railcar.  Between 1040-1112 (1-18-06), the LEPC, SERC and NRC was notified of the incident. At 1500 (1-18-06), arranged with Canadian Pacific Railroad for an empty chlorine railcar (#HOKX 132247) to be moved from their switch yard and re-spotted within Ulrich’s facility.  At 2130 (1-18-06) OXY personnel arrived and were briefed on current status.  Rate of release has not increased and the incident has been stable since 0735.  Decision was made to tighten the bolts on the man-way flange in an attempt to resolve incident.  Applied 750 foot-pounds to each man-way bolt and monitored for improvement.  No improvement was observed, railcar continued to slightly leak product.  At 2300 (1-18-06), the decision was made to shutdown the transferring operation from railcar to ton containers and secure the area.  Ulrich personnel remained on-site over-night to monitor the railcar.  At 0930 (1-19-06), SRS arrived at facility and was briefed on current status of incident.  The following incident response objectives were established:  (1). Railcar #HOKX 132247 will be degassed into Ulrich’s onsite chlorine scrubber system to decrease the internal pressure to approximately 30 psi.  This will allow chlorine to be transferred from leaking car; (2). Trans-load chlorine from car #GATX 44537 to #HOKX 132247 and (3). Prepare car #GATX 44537 for shipment back to OXY Chemical.  At
column169: At this time, there are no recommendations.  Ulrich Chemical's internal procedure of pre-operational inspection of railcars proved to effective measures.

column168: Approximately 300 plastic tubs of regulated medical waste were on the trailer.  The plastic tubs had fallen over while being transported between the generator and the Stericycle facility.  The tubs fell over due to improper loading.  The tubs were not stacked tightly in the trailer.  The leakage was the result of improper packaging (bags were not used in all the containers).      The containers were stacked on the dock at the facility as they were removed from the trailer.  The leakage was absorbed using absorbant pads.  The trailer floor was cleaned and disinfected using a bleach/water solution.  There was little cost involved in the cleanup of the spill.  Stericycle's main concern with the spill is the increased risk to employees involved with the spill clean up of regulated medical waste.
column169: The customer responsible for the improper packaging and improper loading is being notified later today via letter.  If the customer would use bags in all the containers as required in the packaging of regulated medical waste and would properly load the trailer, the likelihood of a spill is very small.

column168: Train No. 211 lifted this load from the Irving Oil Company facility in Searsport and placed it in their train for movement to Northern Maine Jct approximately 29 miles North of Searsport.  During No 211s trip North they had to make a stop at Kidders which is located approximately 2.20 miles North of Searsport. While stopped at Kidders the Conductor noticed that the side of GATX 15252, diesel fuel, was wet below the dome area of the car.  Furher inspection by the Conductor determined that some product had been seeping from the dome area of the car sometime during recent movement, however it was not seeping at this time and it appeared none had reached the ground.  The car was set off at Kidders for further inspection. On January 11, 2006 Irving Oil Company employees changed the dome gasket which was cracked.  Inspection of the ground in different areas between Mile 2.20 and the Irving Terminal at Searsport did not indicate that any product reached the ground during seepage.  The loss of product was minimal and hard to determine. Less than a gallon of seepage was estimated by railroad personnel with none actually reaching the ground.

column168: 0730:NOTIFIED BY TERMINAL PERSONNEL OF A LEAKING TRAILER ON THE KINGSPORT YARD.  0740:NOTIFIED THE EASTMAN FIRE HALL OF A LEAKING TRAILER ON THE KINGSPORT YARD.I ADVISED THEM THAT APPROXIMATELY 1 PINT HAD LEAKED ONTO THE GROUND,AND WE HAD A BUCKET UNDER THE DRIP,AND WE NEEDED AUTHORIZATION TO TRANSLOAD THE PRODUCT TO ANOTHER TRAILER.  0802:RECEIVED CALL FROM TIM BLANKINSHIP(EASTMAN FIRE HALL)HE WANTED FURTHER CLARIFICATION ON THE INCIDENT IN QUESTION.HE ADVISED ME TO STAND BY FOR AUTHORIZATION TO OFFLOAD.  0910:I PLACED A CALL TO THE FIRE HALL TO CHECK ON THE STATUS OF MY AUTHORIZATION TO OFFLOAD THE TRAILER.TIM BLANKINSHIP ADVISED ME THAT SOMEONE FROM THE MATERIALS HANDLING GROUP HAD VISITED THE SCENE AND HAD ALL READY GIVEN THEM VERBAL AUTHORIZATION TO TRANSFER THE LOAD.  TRANSFER OF THE PRODUCT BEGAN AT 0930,AND WAS COMPLETE BY 1200.  02/02/2006 1200: I WAS ADVISED BY THE TANK REPAIR FACILITY THAT THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK WAS A CRACK IN A WELD AT THE SEAM BETWEEN THE TANK AND HEAD ON THE #2 COMPARTMENT.
column169: WE WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT TRAILERS AND CHECK FOR LEAKS.

column168: Rollover accident - Investigation shows that the interstate was dark and pavement dry - traffic was light and the weather clear - 2 lanes headed N on I 55 MM 45 - The Right or east shoulder near 7 foot wide slopes twoard the East about one foot and then the landscape drops continuously toward the East about 5 foot in depth with about 30 foot. Ruts in the soil were viewed at the most southerly point east of the shoulder. Scrapes were found on the pavement in both lanes hearded N near 150 foot to the vehicles resting point.  Driver states "he was startled by a loud "pop" and possibly swerved due to the slope of the shoulder the weight shifted and due to the drop off at the shoulder, driver was not able to recover " The unit rolled and the product that was lost leaked from the cap on the top of the trailer.   Driver was transported from the scene and treated at a local ER for injuires connected w/ the vehicle accident. Driver did not come into contact w/ the product.   MO DOT was on site and assisted w/ clean up and traffic control. Hazmat team, SWS, was contacted to perform clean up of site. Remining product was pumped from damage trailer and delivered to customer.  Driver was terminated from employment due to accident.
column169: More Rollover awareness training. This issue is being discused and emphasised via safety meetings and payroll stuffers.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines driver arrived at customer location to deliver split load of gasoline and had to park on a hill.  Driver set the parking brake and thought he had the truck in gear.  While driver was unloading, the truck started to roll.  The hose broke in two pieces spilling approximately 91 gallons onto concrete.  Product ran off concrete into an empty, dry retaining pond.  SWS responded to the scene and is handling clean up.
column169: Driver should have double checked to make sure that both the tractor and trailer brakes were applied and that the truck was parked in a low gear.  Florida Rock & Tank Lines will go over this incident in all monthly safety meetings company-wide and emphasize the importance of parking in gear.

column42: HYDROGEN PEROXIDE AND PEROXYACETIC ACID MIXTURES, STABILIZED WITH ACIDS, WATER, AND NOT MORE THAN 5 PERCENT PEROXYACETIC ACID
column168: The product consisted of 15-cartons, each containing 4-one gallon plastic bottles. All were on a single pallet that was loaded near the center of the trailer on the top tier of freight. During transit the cartons fell off the pallet to the floor behind and were crushed. The leakage was caused by the   cartons landing upside down, crushing under weight and having self-venting caps.
column169: Freight and dunnage loaded behind this product was not properly blocked and braced against the product, leaving an open hole for it to fall into as it shifted back. A bulkhead or other freight could have prevented this occurrence.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines driver arrived at customer location to unload gasoline.  He verified that the load would fit by sticking the tanks and referring to the tank charts.  After he began to unload, product started backing up and came out of the vapor recovery system.  Driver shut down the flow of product, contained the product on the concrete using spill pads, and notified all appropriate parties.  Initial investigation indicates that the customer's vapor recovery system malfunctioned, causing the spill.
column169: This incident was non-preventable for Florida Rock & Tank Lines.  Our driver followed all proper procedures.  Customer must be sure that their tanks and equipment are properly maintained and in proper working condition.

column25: NGL SUPPLY LTD C/O SUBURBAN PROPANE GAS CO
column168: THE YARDMASTER AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN ST. CLAIR, MI ADVISED THAT A CAR INSPECTOR REPORTED THAT HE COULD HEAR HISSING COMING FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR, NATX 33546, RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED, PETRLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED.  THE YARDMASTER NOTIFIED THE CONSIGNEE, BP CANADA MARKETING, IN ST. CLAIR, MI.  BP RESPONDED A REPRESENTATIVE OF OIL WELL SERVICES (OWS) TO REPAIR THE CAR.  THE SHIPPER, NGL SUPPLY LTD, WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  MR. RICK DORSEY WITH OWS REPORTED THAT HE FOUND THE VAPOR VALVE WAS OPEN AND THE VAPOR VALVE PLUG LESS THAN HAND TIGHT.  HE CLOSED THE VAPOR VALVE AND TIGHTENED ALL THE VALVE PLUGS WRENCH TIGHT.  THE HISSING STOPPED.  HE CHECKED ALL VALVES AND FITTINGS WITH A SOAP SOLUTION AND FOUND NO LEAKS.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO BE DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE.

column168: On 1/23/06, one drum of flammable liquids from East End Body, Inc was discovered to be leaking while in temporary storage at Onyx's ten-day storage facility located in Poca, WV.  The drum failed and leaked 5 gallons of paint and thinner.  The leak was limited to the temporary storage trailer and concrete parking area.  No spilled material migrated to the soil or water.  The original drum appeared to be in good condition.  However, upon further inspection, it appeared as though the paint on the near the bottom of the drum was "bubbled out".  It is believed that the drum deteriorated from the inside out.  The spilled material was cleaned up with spill absorbents and disposed of appropriately.
column169: In the future, the driver picking up material from this shipper will inspect the drums for any paint bubbles.   If any bubbles are detected, the shipper will transfer the material into a new, suitable container for the material.

column168: Univar employee was conducting an IBC to storage tank transfer operation.  After completing the transfer of the 2nd of 3 containers/IBC's, the employee "walked" the hose in order to clear any residual material back into the tank.  When attempting to connect the transfer hose to the next IBC for transfer, some residual material began to spill out of the hose end and contacted the employee.  An estimated 5 pounds of material leaked out from the hose.  Employee was wearing PPE but, some of the nitric acid splashed onto his neck area. He immediately went to safety shower to decontaminate.  He was treated by site EHS personnel and sent to hospital for observation.  He was released that same morning with a small chemical burn on the left side of his neck.  The residual spilled material was cleaned up by site personnel.
column169: The following corrective measures implemented:    1) Work procedures were revised to require capping of transfer hoses prior to IBC connection.    2) Drivers have been retrained to conduct more effective line clearing.    3) Enhanced PPE now required for IBC to tank transfers.

A Halliburton employee was driving east on Styles Rd. There was a stop sign at Styles and Hwy. 132. As the employee made a left turn onto Hwy. 132, one of the totes came from under the securing staps and skidded across the bed of the truck. The tote then struck the guard rail and broke the securing pin, causing the tote to fall off the truck. The container hit the road and burst open. Approximately ten gallons spilled on the highway and the remainer ran off into the bar ditch. The employee contacted his immediate supervisor. The immediate supervisor contacted the state police, sheriff, D.O.T. and his supervisor. Halliburton contacted a third party for the cleanup. Third party came to the site to remidiate the affected area and properly disposed of the waste caused by the spill.
column169: Employees will be re-trained in the proper securement of loads.

column168: Driver was offloading product from cargo tank into customer’s storage tank when customer operator noticed a minute leak from the transfer hose fitting.  Driver immediately stopped the transfer and closed the trailer valves.  Operator evacuated hose into their system.  Drivers and operators found set screw had loosened and hose sleeve had turned, allowing for material to leak out.  Drivers and operators reassembled the fitting and tightened the set screw.  Fitting no longer leaked, and delivery was completed.  Less than 1 pound of material was released.  No evacuations were made, no injuries reported, and no complaints of off-site odor were recorded.
column169: Additional training provided to drivers and operators regarding the set screw on the transfer hoses and how to check that it is tight before use.

column168: WILBUR-ELLIS COMPANY TRUCK PULLING A 1,000 GALLON CARGO TANK TRAILER WAS WEST BOUND ON FM ROAD 221 NEAR EL CONEJO ROAD.  THE VEHICLE WENT OVER A SHARP RISE ACROSS THE ROADWAY (REPAIRED TRENCH) CAUSING THE CARGO TANK TO RISE AND THEN DROP BACK TO THE ROADWAY.  THE DROP CAUSED A SMALL 2-INCH CRACK IN THE POLYETHYLENE TANK SIDEWALL AT A MOUNTING STRAP.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY PULLED OFF THE ROADWAY (ABOUT 30 FEET) AND CALLED WILBUR-ELLIS COMPANY FOR ASSISTANCE.  THE ROADWAY WAS NOT BLOCKED.  ALL OF THE LIQUID FERTILIZER SPILLED ON DIRT AWAY FROM THE EDGE OF THE ROADWAY.  WILBUR-ELLIS COMPANY PERSONNEL EVALUATED THE SPILL LOCATION AND DETERMINED THE FOLLOWING: 1. NO LIQUID FERTILIZER WAS STANDING.  2.  NO ABOVE GROUND WATER WAS WITHIN A 15-MILE RADIUS.  3.  AREA DOES NOT DRAIN INTO NAVIGABLE WATERS.  4.  NO DRINKING WATER WELLS WITHIN A 15-MILE RADIUS.  5.  UNDERGROUND WATER IN THE AREA IS NOT POTABLE.  6. LAND IN THIS AREA IS DESIGNATED FOR DRY LAND FARMING OF COTTON.  7.  THE SPILL DID NOT MEET THE DEFINITION OF A REPORTABLE QUANTITY OF ANY HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE.  8.  THE ABSORBER FERTILIZER DID NOT POSE A HEALTH PROBLEM TO PERSONS, THE ENVIRONMENT OR AGRICULTURAL CROPS.
column169: WILBUR-ELLIS COMPANY DRIVER HAS BEEN COUNSELED ABOUT THE IMPORTANCE OF REDUCING SPEED ON ROUGH ROADWAYS OR ROADS UNDER CONSTRUCTION.

column168: Driver had made a succesful delivery prior to leak. Upon arrival at the shipper driver proceeded to load trailer. When trailer was approximately half full driver went to the rear of the trailer to check the delivery valve as it had felt "soft" at prior delivery. He felt he was in a better position at the shipper to fix any problems before proceeding to the consingee. Upon removing the cap from the delivery pipe product poured out of the delivery pipe. Driver immediately "slammed" cap back on in an attempt to stop the flow. At this point sulfur was being discharged through the cam lock openings on the cap. Driver advised the operator to stop the loading process.
column169: Company supervisory and safety personnel were called to the scene. Driver and operator utilized a nearby water canon to direct cold water on the delivery pipe.  By this time product flow had slowed to a trickle. The trailer was moved forward into a constructed dike of bank run sand and trailer was allowed to discharge into this dike area. Company personnel contained and cleaned up spill.

column169: The cargo tank was inspected after the incident and it appears the inside of the tank was corroded from some prior product.  It is very difficult for us as the transporter to determine the corrosive effect of products on our 316 stainless steel trailers when the products are usually a mixture of chemicals.  It would be great if all shippers did corrosion testing with their product before offering it for shipment.  Right now, if the shipper doesn't provide corrosion data, all we have to rely on are corrosion reference books but that limits us to one chemical at a time.

column168: Driver was northbound on SR45 and upon entering a left-hand curve, he got too wide and got off the road on the outside of the curve.  The soil apron along the highway was soft due to above normal temperatures and rain earlier in the month.  Once the tractor and trailer were off the pavement, driver could not pull them back onto the roadway.  The ground sloped down and away from the roadway about 4 or 5 feet.  The slope away from the roadway caused the tractor-trailer to lean and rollover, finally coming to rest with the tractor on its wheels and the trailer laying on its right side.  The twisting action on the trailer caused small leaks in the tank barrel and piping.  Immediately the responding fire department helped the driver then proceeded to plug, absorb or collect any spilled product in containers.  Upon Frette Energy's arrival on the scene with another tractor-trailer, all product from the wrecked vehicle was transferred into another trailer and the fuel from the tractor saddle tank was transferred into the other trailer.  Pads and booms were placed at the entry into a culvert to prevent any product from entering and thereby prohibiting the product from migrating under SR45 and into the soil.
column169: All company employees were required to attend a mandatory meeting on the next business day to update them on the facts of the incident and to remind them of the basic properties of liquid transport and tanker rollover potential as well as company policies in reference to all safety rules.  The tractor and trailer had current inspections and the equipment was maintained properly.  Employees were advised to always be vigilant in the course of operating a commercial motor vehicle in respect to all aspects of the operation.

ON 1/20/06, THE SHIPPER(NYK) ADVISED BNSF THAT CONTAINER NYKU 807303 MAY HAVE BEEN MISBILLED AND THAT IT MAY CONTAIN REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  NYKU 807303 (WHICH WAS NOT PLACARDED) WAS HELD AT THE INTERMODAL FACILITY UNTIL NYK COULD DETERMINE FROM THE OVERSEAS ORGIN ON ITS PROPER BILLING STATUS.  ON 1/26/06, NYK CONFIRMED THAT NYKU 807303 DID CONTAIN A REGULATED CLASS 6.1 SUBSTANCE AND NYK FURNISHED BNSF WITH THE CORRECTED BILLING DOCUMENTATION FOR THIS SHIPMENT.  NYKU 807303 WAS REBILLED ACCORDINGLY FROM THE NEW SHIPPING INFORMATION RECEIVED FROM NYKU 807303 WAS PLACARDED AND OUTGATED FROM THE BNSF CICERO INTERMODAL HUB ON 1/27/03.

column168: FLATCAR VTTX 97567, WITH 2 INTERMODAL CONTAINERS TPHU 681321 AND MSCU 376266, WAS INVOLVED IN A MAINLINE DERAILMENT RESULTING IN DAMAGE AND LOSS OF PRODUCT FROM BOTH CONTAINERS. ALL FEDERAL, STATE AND LOCAL AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTORS ONE STOP ENVIRONMENTAL AND HEPACO WERE CALLED AND RESPONDED TO ASSIST IN ENVIRONMENTAL ASSESSMENT AND CLEAN-UP. CTEH CONDUCTED AIR MONITORING AT THE SITE AND AROUND THE PERIMETER OF THE INCIDENT LOCATION.  TPHU 681321, LOADED WITH 30 GALLON STEEL, REMOVABLE HEAD DRUMS, WAS DAMAGED RESULTING IN THE LOSS OF 250 POUNDS OF MATERIAL DURING THE INCIDENT AND SUBSEQUENT CLEAN-UP. ALL RELEASED MATERIAL WAS RECOVERED AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF.  MSCU 376266, LOADED WITH 20 INTERMEDIATE BULK CONTAINERS SUSTAINED DAMAGE TO 1 OF THE 20 IBC'S RESULTING IN THE LOSS OF 35 POUNDS OF MATERIAL DURING THE INCIDENT AND SUBSEQUENT CLEAN-UP. ALL THE RELEASED MATERIAL WAS RECOVERED AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF.  THE CONTENTS OF THE DAMAGED CONTAINERS WAS OVERPACKED AS NECESSARY AND TRANSFERRED TO NEW CONTAINERS OR WATERTIGHT ROLL-OFF CONTAINERS AND RETURNED TO THE ORIGIN SHIPPER FOR FURTHER INSPECTION AND HANDLING.  THE EVACUATION OF 300 PEOPLE IS AN ESTIMATE BASED ON THE POPULATION OF THE EVACUATED AREA. THE POPULATION WAS ADVISED BY LOCAL EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT OFFICIALS TO SHELTER IN PLACE OR LEAVE THE EVACUATION ZONE. TWO HOUSES IMMEDAITELY ADJACENT TO THE SITE WERE EVACUATED UNTIL AFTER ALL HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WERE REMOVED FROM THE SITE OR ABOUT 50 HOURS. LOCAL OFFICIALS WERE UNSURE OF AN EXACT NUMBER OF EVACUEES OR DURATION OF THE EVACUATION.

A RAIL CAR WAS LOADED WITH ANHYDROUS AMMONIA EARLY ON A FOGGY, COLD SATURDAY MORNING.  WHEN THE RAIL CAR REACHED THE INTENDED LOADED WEIGHT, THE AUTOMATIC LOADING SYSTEM SHUT DOWN THE LOADING PUMPS, AND SIGNALED THE RAIL CAR LOADING LINE SHUT-OFF VALVE TO CLOSE.  SHORTLY AFTERWARD, A TRUCK DRIVER STARTED LOADING AMMONIA.  THE RAIL CAR LOAD LINE AND THE TRUCK LOADING LINE SHARE A COMMON HEADER.  EACH LINE IS EQUIPPED WITH A SHUT-OFF VALVE THAT ALLOWS LOADING FROM EITHER LINE OR BOTH.  THE SHUT-OFF VALVES ARE AIR OPERATED, AND CLOSE WHEN THE ACTUATOR OPENS THE EXHAUST LINE, WHICH IS A 1/4-INCH STAINLESS TUBING LINE.  DURING THE LOADING OF A TRUCK, THE RAIL CAR OVERFILLED, AND THE RAIL CAR RELIEF VALVE OPENED, RELEASING A CLOUD OF AMMONIA VAPOR.  THE CLOUD EXTENDED TO THE CONTROL ROOM.  THE OPERATORS ACTIVATED THE LOADING AREA EMERGENCY SHUTDOWN SYSTEM FROM THE CONTROL ROOM, SHUTTING OFF ALL LOADING.  THE RAIL CAR RELIEF VALVE RESEATED ITSELF, AND THE VAPOR CLOUD QUICKLY DISSIPATED.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR OTHER PERSONNEL IMPACTS FROM THE INCIDENT.  THE AMOUNT OF THE RELEASE WAS 1,400 POUNDS.  THE MITIGATION MEASURES AND RAPID RESPONSE ACTIONS TAKEN PREVENTED SIGNIFICANT IMPACT BEYOND WHAT DID OCCUR.  NEITHER THE TRUCK DRIVER NOR THE ON-SITE OPERATORS WERE AFFECTED BY THE AMMONIA RELEASE.  THE INCIDENT DID RESULT IN A BRIEF SHELTER-IN-PLACE FOR THE OPERATING CREW UNTIL THE AMMONIA CLUD DISSIPATED.  THE RELEASE WAS REPORTED TO THE STATE AGENCIES AND THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER.  IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE AIR EXHAUST TUBE ON THE RAIL CAR SHUT-OFF VALVE WAS PLUGGED WITH ICE.  THE UNIT WAS TAKEN TO THE SHOP FOR INSPECTION.  ONCE THE ICE PLUG WAS REMOVED, THE PNEUMATIC SYSTEM OPERATED NORMALLY, AS DESIGNED.  MOST PROBABLE CAUSE OF THE ICE PLUG WAS THE FREEZING FOG IN THE AREA THAT MORNING.  DURING THE SUBSEQUENT INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT IF THE AIR IS NOT EXHAUSTED FROM THE VALVE ACTUATOR, THE VALVE CAN FAIL TO CLOSE.  AT THE TIME, WERE NO MEANS IN PLACE TO VERIFY THAT THE LOAD LINE VALVE HAD CLOSED ONCE THE LOAD SYSTEM WAS SHUT DOWN.  IMMEDIATE CORRECTIVE ACTION ARE TO REPLACE THE 1/4-INCH TUBING WITH A LARGER OPENING, TO HELP REDUCE POSSIBLE PLUGGING FROM ICE.  LONG-TERM CORRECTIVE ACTIONS ARE TO INSTALL A SYSTEM THAT ALARMS OPERATIONS WHEN THE VALVE FAILS TO CLOSE, AND WHCIH IS EQUIPPE3D WITH AN AUTOMATIC INTERLOCK THAT SHUTS DOWN THE LOADING PUMPS UNTIL THE VALVE ON THE IDLE LINE IS CLOSED.  BECAUSE LARGER TUBING COULD RESULT IN OTHER CAUSES OF BLOCKAGE, IT WILL BE REPLACED WITH A 1/4-INCH STANDARD SIZE AT THAT TIME.
column169: IMMEDIATE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS ARE TO REPLACE THE 1.4 INCH TUBING WITH A LARGER OPENING, TO HELP REDUCE POSSIBLE PLUGGING FROM ICE. LONG-TERM CORRECTIVE ACTIONS ARE TO INSTALL A SYSTEM THAT ALARMS OPERATIONS WHEN THE VALVE FAILS TO CLOSE, AND WHICH IS EQUIPPED WITH AN AUTOMATIC INTERLOCK THAT SHUTS DOWN THE LOADING PUMPS UNTIL THE VALVE ON THE IDLE LINE IS CLOSED. THE LARGER TUBING WILL BE REPLACED WITH THE 1/4 INCH STANDARD SIZE AT THAT TIME.

column168: 0N 01/19/06, A KC INDUSTRIES TRUCKING DRIVER WAS AT THE CAPE CORAL, CITY WATER TREATMENT PLANT IN CAPE CORAL, FLORIDA TO UNLOAD SULFURIC ACID (SA).  THE DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE PLANT AT APPROXIMATELY 6:00 PM.  A CAPE CORAL EMPLOYEE OPENED THE GATE AND THE DRIVER DROVE TO THE UNLOADING SITE AND STARTED THE UNLOADING PROCESS.  DURING THE PROCESS, A SMALL HOLE IN THE WELD LOCATED BY THE UNLOADING LINE BEGAN TO LEAK.  A BUCKET WAS PLACED UNDER THE LEAK TO CATCH THE ACID.  THE ACID CAUSED THE AIRLINE TO DETERIORATE.  THE AIRLINE LOST PRESSURE AND THE AIR ACTUATOR VALVE LOCATED AT THE TANKER OUTLET LINE AUTOMATICALLY CLOSED.  THE TANKER HAD BEEN PRESSURIZED FOR THE UNLOADING PROCESS.  WHEN THE AIR ACTUATOR VALVE AUTOMATICALLY CLOSED AT APPROXIMATELY 6:30 PM, THE PRESSURE IN THE TANK CAUSED THE LEAK TO INCREASE IN VOLUME.  THE PRESSURE INCREASED IN THE TANKER BECAUSE THE UNLOADING PROCESS HAD STOPPED.  THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE LOCATED ON THE TOP OF THE TANKER RELEASED PRESSURE.  THIS ALERTED THE DRIVER AND THE OPERATOR THAT THERE WAS A PROBLEM AND THEY NOTICED THE AIR ACTUATOR VALVE HAD CLOSED AND THAT THE LEAK HAD INCREASED IN VOLUME.  A PLANT OPERATOR PLACED A LARGER CONTAINER UNDER THE LEAK AND CALLED THE LEE COUNTY HAZMAT EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM.  THE DRIVER DOUBLE CHECKED ALL OF HIS AIR CONNECTIONS AND DETERMINED THAT HE COULD NOT REOPEN THE AIR ACTUATOR VALVE.  AT THIS POINT, THE DRIVER DISCONNECTED THE UNLOADING HOSE.  A PLANT OPERATOR MOVED THE CONTAINER THAT WAS CATCHING THE ACID WITH A FORKLIFT AND THE DRIVER MOVED THE TRUCK TO THE CONTAINMENT AREA.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SITE, THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, ACT WAS ABLE TO RELEASE THE PRESSURE IN THE TANK AND STOP THE LEAK.  THE REMAINING MATERIAL IN THE TANKER WAS OFF LOADED INTO ANOTHER TANK ON SITE.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL HAD BEEN CAPTURED IN THE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT FOR THE LOADING DOCK.  THE MATERIAL WAS RELEASED INTO THE CAPE CORAL WATER TREATMENT FACILITY WHERE IT WAS NEUTRALIZED AND RELEASED TO THE LOCAL POTW.  THE CONCRETE AREAS THAT WERE IMPACTED WERE RINSED WITH ALL RESIDUE.  FROM THE TIME THE ER CONTRACTOR ARRIVED ON SITE TO THE DISCARGE OF THE NEUTRALIZED MATERIAL, THE DURATION WAS APPROXIMATELY 12 HOURS.  WHAT CAUSED THE ACCIDENT?  LOOSE U-BOLT.  THE U-BOLT THAT HOLDS THE OUTLET PIPE AND OUTLET VALVE TO THE BRACKET WAS LOOSE, ALLOWING IT TO MOVE AND PUT STRESS ON THE WELD CAUSING A PINHOLE LEAK.  ROOT CAUSE:  INADEQUATE MAINTENANCE INSPECTION AND/OR MONITORING.

REVISE PRE-TRIP AND POST-TRIP INSPECTION FORM TO INCLUDE ADDITIONAL SPECIFIC CRITICAL AREAS.  RE-TRAIN DRIVERS ON IN-DEPTH TANKER AND TRUCK INSPECTIONS.

column168: The driver had to apply the brakes suddenly causing the load to shift. When the driver stopped to inspect the load, he observed paint dripping from the trailer. The pails were placed in 55-gallon drums along with granular sorbents and sorbent pads used to absorb the spilled paint from the trailer and the asphalt.  The five drums containing damaged 5-gallon pails and spill cleanup debris were transported to a permitted disposal facility.

AFTERWARDS, THE RESIDUE PRODUCT SMELL WAS STILL DETECTABLE. A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CONTRACT RESPONDER WAS CALLED-IN TO INSPECT GATX 26771 AND LOCATE THE SOURCE OF THE ODOR. PRELIMINARY INVESTIGATION POINTED TOWARDS THE MAGNETIC GAUGING DEVICE'S THREADED BASE AT THE PRESSURE PLATE. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED NO DETECTABLE LEAK AT THIS FITTING. CONSIGNEE RESPONDERS ARRIVED AND MEASURED RESIDUE PRODUCT VAPOR ESCAPING AT THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE OR SAFETY RELIEF VALVE (PRD OR SRV) AT APPROXIMATELY 11 PM. FURTHER INVESTIGATION BY THESE RESPONDERS UNCOVERED A LOOSE RETAINER NUT (TOP LOCK NUT) ON THE RETAINER (ALSO REFERRED TO AS THE O-RING KEEPER). RESPONDERS TOOL TIGHTENED THIS RETAINER NUT BY APPROXIMATELY 2300 HRS. CST 1/18/06. AFTER SECUREMENT WAS COMPLETED NO FURTHER PRODUCT VAPOR OR ODOR WAS DETECTABLE. THE PRD/SRV SPECIFICATION STENCILED INSPECTION DATE ON GATX 26771 WAS 2005 ARIB.

BNSF SWITCHMAN REPORTED PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM AROUND THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE (BOV) AREA OF UTLX 202453 IN THE RAILYARD. UTLX 202453 WAS CAREFULLY MOVED TO THE RAILYARD CONTAINMENT AREA (RAIL CAR DRIP PIT) FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION. CONTRACT RESPONDERS INVESTIGATING CONFIRMED THAT THE BOTTOM OPERATED BOV WAS THE LEAK SOURCE. PRODUCT WAS DRIPPING FROM THE THREADED BOTTOM OUTLET CAP (BOC). THE BOV WAS IN THE CLOSED POSITION. THE BOC WAS REMOVED AND TEFLON TAPE APPLIED TO ITS THREADED AREA AND ADDITIONAL GASKET MATERIAL APPLIED INSIDE THE BOC. THE BOC WAS REAPPLIED AND TOOL TIGHTENED WHICH ELIMINATED FURTHER PRODUCT DRIP ON 1/13/06. ALL SPILLAGE HAD EVAPORATED. A DETERMINATION WAS MADE THAT TOO MUCH PRODUCT MAY BE BY PASSING THE CLOSED BOV. FRA MOVEMENT APPROVAL FRA 06010010 WAS RECEIVED TO TRANSPORT UTLX 202453 TO ITS DESTINATION FOR UNLOADING; AND AFTERWARDS, UTLX 202453 TO BE DIRECTED TO A REPAIR FACILITY FOR BOV TESTING AND NECESSARY REPAIRS. A NEW BOC WAS ORDERED AND IT ARRIVED ON 1/17/06 NUT THE INTERIOR  BOC GASKET WAS THOUGHT TO BE TOO THIN. CONTRACT RESPONDERS FABRICATED A THICKER GASKET AND APPLIED IT TO THE NEW BOC ON 1/20/06. AGAIN, NO PRODUCT DRIPPAGE WAS EVIDENT AFTER THE NEW BOC WAS SECURED. UTLX 202453 WAS RELEASED TO PROCEED TO DESTINATION AT 1413 HRS. CST1 1/20/06.

column168: Tank had 1600 gallons before the delivery and the order was for 1000 gallons into a 3000 gallon tank. About 10 gallons spilled from the vent at 996 gallons into an alley between two buildings.      Serviceman from Stuyvesant Fuel came to the location and it was found that the root cause of the spill was due to a gad gauge.

column168: PETRON TRUCK 502 AND TRAILER 1091 WAS LOADED WITH 6348 GALLONS OF NATURAL GAS CONDENSATE, LABELED UN 3295, FROM THE MOORE COMPRESSOR STATION WHICH IS A PIPELINE LOCATION. DRIVER DAVID LEVIAS ATTEMPTED TO CROSS THE RAILROAD TRACKS WHEN THE TRAILER WAS STRUCK BY A UNION PACIFIC TRAIN. UPON IMPACT THE TANK TRAILER RUPTURED THERE WAS AN EXPLOSION AND FIRE. ALL EMERGENCY AGENCIES WERE CALLED FIRE AND POLICE. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR FATALITIES. THE AREA OF THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND NO WATER WAYS WERE INVOLVED. LLANO- PERIMAN ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CONTRACTED TO DO CONTAINMENT AND CLEAN UP THE CONTACT FOR LLANO-PERIMAN IS JASON LINCOLN (806) 681-9257. AT 1115 HOURS WE CONTACTED RANDELL PATTERSON OF THE TEXAS RAILROAD COMMISSION OIL AND GAS HAULERS TO REPORT THE INCIDENT. BECAUSE THE INCIDENT OCCURRED IN FAYETTE COUNTY HE DIRECTED ME TO RAILROAD COMMISSION DISTRICT OFFICE #3. I CALLED THE DISTRICT OFFICE AND WAS DIRECTED TO GIL BUJANO. MR. BUJANO WAS NOT IN AND A MESSAGE WAS LEFT. I WAS CALLED BACK AT 1125 HOURS BY DOUG STORY HE INFORMED ME THAT A RAILROAD COMMISSION OFFICIAL WAS IN ROUTE AND THAT MR. BUJANO WOULD CALL ME SOON. AT 1130 HOURS MR. BUJANO CALLED AND ASKED FOR A REPORT TO BE FAXED TO (713) 869-9621. AT 1145 HOURS SPILL REPORTING WAS CALLED 800-832-8224. THE REPORT WAS TAKEND BY ED MURPHY AND REPORT #20060206 WAS ASSIGNED TO THE INCIDENT. AT 1155 HOURS CLAUDIA CHAFFIN OF THE TCEQ CALLED TO SAY THEY HAD BEEN INFORMED OF THE INCIDENT AND TO SEND A REPORT TO (512) 339-3795. TXDOT WAS CALLED AT 1420 HOURS TO REPORT THE INCIDENT. THE AUSTIN OFFICE WAS CALLED (512) 832-7000 THEY DIRECTED ME TO CHRIS BISHOP (512) 832-7110, MR. BISHOP DIRECTED ME TO PEGGY KERJCI (361) 293-4300, MS. KERJCI WAS NOT IN AND I WAS DIRECTED TO LONNIE GREGORCIK. MR. GREGORCIK WAS UNSURE WHAT TO DO AND SAID HE WOULD CALL ME BACK. MR. GERGORCIK HAD NOT RETURNED MY CALL BY 1545 HOURS SO I CALLED BACK AND WAS INFORMED HE HAD LEFT FOR THE DAY NO OTHER PERSONNEL WERE ABLE TO HELP ME SO I LEFT A MESSAGE. AT 1600 HOURS THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS CALLED 800-424-8802 MR. CREWS TOOK THE REPORT AND ASSIGNED IT #785808 TO THE INCIDENT. AN MSDS OF THE PRODUCT INVOLVED WILL ACCOMPANY THIS INCIDENT REPORT.

column168: 01/06/2006  DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE DELIVERY SITE, A WAWA CONVENIENCE STORE, AT APPROXIMATELY 0500 LOADED WITH 7000 GALLONS REGULAR GAS AND 2000 GALLONS PREMIUM GAS.  AFTER SECURING THE TRUCK, THE DRIVER OBTAINED COPIES OF THE VEEDER-ROOT FROM THE STORE DO DETERMINE QUANTITIES IN THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANKS.  DRIVER THEN CONNECTED HIS VAPOR HOSES TO THE VAPOR RECOVERY ON THE REGULAR AND PREMIUM TANKS.  THE DRIVER STUCK THE TANKS AND ALONG WITH THE VEEDER-ROOT DETERMINED THAT HE HAD SPACE FOR 9000 GALLONS IN THE PREMIUM TANK AND MORE THAN 5000 GALLONS IN EACH OF THE REGULAR TANKS.  THE DRIVER THEN CONNECTED HIS DELIVERY HOSE TO FIRST THE REGULAR TANK AND THEN TO THE PREMIUM TANK AND STARTED HIS DELIVERY.  WHEN THE DRIVER TURNED AWAY FROM THE PREMIUM TANK, HE HEARD A SOUND COMMING FROM THE FILL THAT GO HIS ATTENTION.  HE TURNED BACK AROUND TO FIND GAS STREAMING OUT FROM THE PLUNGER AREA IN THE CONTAINMENT WELL.  HE IMMEDIATELY SHUT HIS DISCHARGE VALVE, GRABBED HIS SPILL KIT AND BEGAN TO CONTAIN THE SPILL WITH STAY-DRY AND ABSORBENT BOOMS.  AFTER THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED, THE DRIVER NOTIFIED THE STORE MANAGER WHO CALLED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT.  SHORTLY AFTERWARDS, A MANAGER FROM S. CORALUZZO ARRIVED ON THE SCENE.  HE AND THE STORE MANAGER CHECKED THE PREMIUM FILL AREA.  THE CONTAINMENT WELL STILL CONTAINED PRODUCT AND THE MANAGERS OBSERVED EXTREMELY HIGH PRESSURE COMING FROM THE PREMIUM TANK.  THE STORE MANAGER EITHER CALLED OR NOTIFIED HIS CORPORATE OFFICE TO SUMMON TANK MAINTENANCE PERSONNEL.  CAMDEN COUNTY AND BERLLIN BOROUGH EPA WERE PRESENT.  LEWIS ENVIRONMENTAL ARRIVED AAND WAS TASKED TO DO THE CLEANUP.  AS THE PRESSURE IN THE PREMIUM TANK SUBSIDED, THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO FINISH HIS DELIVERY WITH HIS DISCHARGE VALVE HALF OPEN.  THE REGULAR WAS ALSO DELIVERED WITHOUT ANY PROBLEMS.  THE TANK MAINTENANCE PERSONNEL INSPECTED AND REMOVED THE BALL CHECK FRO THE PREMIUM TANK VAPOR RETURN.  SUBSEQUENT DELIVERIES MADE TO THE PREMIUM TANK WERE WITHOUT INCIDENT.  EXCESSIVE BACK PRESSURE FROM A STUCK OR DEFECTIVE BALL CHECK COMBINED WITH VAPOR PRESSURE RETURNING FROM THE PUMPS, MAY HAVE CAUSED THE PRODUCT TO SPEW BACK OUT OF THE TANK. column168: SCHENECTADY INTERNATIONAL INC. (SII) EMPLOYEE CONNECTED ISOBUTYLENE LIQUID AND VENT HOSES TO HERCULES TRUCK #3104.  ALMOST IMMEDIATELY (1 1/2 MINUTES) HE BEGAN HEARING HISSING FROM THE TOP OF THE TRUCK AND SUSPENDING FILLLING OPERATIONS.  UPON INVESTIGATION THE TOP CENTER RELIEF VALVE WAS FOUND LEAKING ALTHOUGH ZERO PRESSURE WAS INDICATED ON TRUCK GAUGE.  THERE ARE THREE RELIEF VALVES ON TOP.  THE RELIEF VALVES ARE SET AT 125 PSIG.  THE RELIEF VALVE IN QUESTION WAS DATED 04/04.  THE TRUCK HAD ALSO ARRIVED WITH NO PRESSURE.  (THE HERCULES DRIVER STATED THE TRUCK HAD RECENTLY BEEN SENT FOR WASHING BY HERCULES AND PURGED WITH NITROGEN.)  TO REREDUCE EMISSIONS DURING THIS EVENT, A SHEET OF GORTEX GASKET MATERIAL, A BLIND PLATE, AND A CONCRETE BLOCK WERE PLACED ON TOP OF THE RECESSED AREA CONTAINING THE RELIEF VALVE.  THE TRUCK LEVEL INDICATION SHOWED LESS THAN THE MINIMUM READING OF 5%.  THE TRUCK PRESSURE GAUGE SHOWED NO PRESSURE.  THE TRUCK WAS THEN SLOWLY VENTED TO THE FLARE HEADER OVER A 2 1/2HR PERIOD.  THE FLARE SMOKED UNTIL ADDITIONAL ASSIST GAS WAS DIRECTED TO THE FLARE, THEN BURNED CLEAN.  GRIT WAS REMOVED FROM THE RECESSED RELIEF VALVE AREA, AND A WOODEN HANDLE WAS USED TO TAP THE CENTER CONE OF THE RELIEF VALVE RESEATING IT ENOUGH TO STOP THE LEAKING.  NO BUBBLES OCCURRED WHEN SOAPY WATER WAS USED TO CHECK FOR LEAKS.  THE TRUCK WAS SENT OUT EMPTY.  NO INJURIES.  PROBABLE ROOT CAUSES?  GRIT ALLOWED TO ACCUMULATE IN RELIEF VALVE CAVITY.  IMMEDIATE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS:  RELIEF VALVE REPAIR SHOP LISTED ON VALVE TAG WAS CONSULTED FOR ADVICE.  MINIMIZED LEAK TO ATMOSPHERE BY ROUTING GASES TO FLARE.  MATERIAL INVOLVED: ISOBUTYLENE QUANTITY:  25 LBS TO ATM, 462.5 LBS TO FLARE.  BASED ON THE FLARE BURNING EFFICIENCY, 62 LBS EMITTED TO AIR.
column169: LONG-TERM ACTION SUGGESTED:  DISCUSSED WITH TRUCKING COMPANY TO ENSURE VALVES FOR TRUCK ARE SEATED BEFORE DELIVERY.  WILL NOT LOAD TRUCKS THAT ARRIVE WITH LESS THAN 10-20 PSIG PRESSURE.

column168: AFTER REVIEWING THE FACTS AND AN EXTENDED INSPECTION ON THE UNIT, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THERE WAS NO MECHANICAL FAILURE. THE ACCIDENT WAS AS A RESULT OF DRIVER'S ERROR. THE DRIVER FAILED TO INSPECT THE UNIT AFTER ATTEMPTING TO COUPLE HIS ASSIGNED UNIT, HAD THE DRIVER INSPECTED THE COUPLING DEVICE, HE WOULD HAVE DISCOVERED THAT THE UNIT WAS NOT COUPLED PROPERLY. THE KING PIN OF THE TRAILER WAS RESTING ON TOP OF THE TRACTOR FIFTH WHEEL'S JAWS (BETTER KNOWN AS "HIGH HOOK").  IN A NORMAL HOOK UP, THE KING PIN IS WRAPPED AROUND BY THE FIFTH WHEEL'S JAWA PREVENTING IT FROM SLIPPING OUT.
column169: AS A RESULT, THE DRIVER'S EMPLOYMENT WAS TERMINATED. THE COMPANY IS ADDING TO THEIR MONTHLY SAFETY MEETING, SPECIAL TRAINING SECTION ON THE COUPLING PROCEDURES, THE TRAINING INCLUDES THE VIEWING OF VIDEO, QUIZ, QUESTIONS ANSWER AND ON SITE DEMONSTRATION ON COUPLING AND UNCOUPLING.

THE CYLINDER WAS LEAKING UPON ARRIVAL AT THE CENTER.  A VAPOR CLOUD WAS IN THE TRAILER AND THE DOOR WAS IMMEDIATELY SHUT AND PROPER PROCEDURES FOR A CHEMICAL RELEASE WERE FOLLOWED.  THE LA STATE POLICE WERE CALLED AND RESPONDED AS WELL AS A CONTRACTOR FROM FEDEX FREIGHT, INC.  THE CAUSE OF THE CLOULD WAS DETERMINED BY RESPOPNDERS AS ATHE BORON TRIFLOURIDE.  THE CYLINDER WAS LEAKING FROM THE VALVE AND COULD NOT BE CONTAINED BY OUTSIDE MEASURES.  A RESPRESENTATIVE FROM HONEYWELL CAME TO THE SCENE AND INSTRUCTED THE RESPONDERS IN PROPER NEUTRALIZATION OF THE PRODUCT.  THE CYLINDER WAS THEN OVERPACKED AND RETURNED TO HONEYWELL.              ALL PRODUCT WAS ABSORBED WITH OIL DRY AND PALCED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  ALL DAMAGED PRODUCT WAS HANDLED ACCORDING TO ALL LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS.
column169: RESPONSIBLE ASSOCIATE(S) HAVE BEEN SHOWN PROPER FREIGHT  HANDLING AND LOADING TECHNIQUES AS WELL AS RECERTIFICATION FOR FORKLIFT OPERATON IF NECESSARY.    HONEYWELL HAS STATED THAT THE VALVES THEY ARE USING WILL BE INSPECTED DUE TO POSSIBLE FAULTS IN MANUFACTURING TO AVOID ANY FURTHER ISSUES CONCERNING THE VALVES.

Driver was in process of unloading 2,500 gallons of diesel fuel into an above ground tank. He properly hooked up all unloading hoses. The load had to be pumped off the trailer into the above ground tank. The pump is located on the tractor unit. When he turned on the pump, the driver noticed that the pump sounded like it was restricted. The pump itself has a T design. A hose was connected to one side and the other side had a steel cap on it. When the pump became restricted it blew the cap off the other side and allowed product to come out of the pump. The product flow was immediately shut off and the pump turned off. Approximately 50 gallons of product was spilled on the asphalt lot. Personnel at the construction site and our driver threw down spill pads and OIL DRI to contain product.
column169: Keep training drivers on proper use of pumps, possible problems that could occur and procedures to take in case pump fails or becomes restricted as in incident.

column168: On January 26, 2006 at approximately 2:15 AM, a representative of Nucor Steel – Arkansas (Nucor) was contacted by Chemtrec with notification that a truck carrying EAF Dust (EPA Listed Hazardous Waste – K061)  had a leak. The driver of the truck reported that after stopping for a break at a gas station in Ozark, Arkansas, he inspected his truck prior to resuming his trip. Upon inspection at approximately 2 AM, he noticed a liquid leaking from the back tailgate of the truck. After observing the leak, he contacted Chemtrec who in turn contacted Nucor. A representative of Nucor immediately contacted the National Reporting Center (NRC), the Arkansas Department of Emergency Management (ADEM) and the Arkansas State Police to report the suspected release. The truck was in transit from Nucor’s facility in Blytheville, Arkansas to a disposal facility in Lone Mountain, Oklahoma owned by Clean Harbors, Inc.    Response:  The driver’s immediate response to the leak was to tighten turn buckles on the tailgate to increase the pressure on the tailgate gaskets. The driver reported that after tightening turn buckles, a small drip was still present. After reporting the release to officials, Nucor contacted HEPACO emergency response contractors based in Little Rock, AR. They immediately dispatched a crew to the site of the release. Upon arrival, they assessed that the situation was safe and posed no danger to the public. They applied absorbent material inside of the truck trailer to absorb any free liquids. Once the free liquids had been absorbed, the trailer’s tailgate was opened for inspection. After representatives from Nucor arrived to inspect the truck, the tailgate was closed and secured. Protective plastic sheeting was placed on the ground to ensure no EAF dust came in contact with the ground. After inspection, the sheeting was rolled up and placed in with the EAF dust for disposal.    Suspected Cause:  The EAF dust normally has no free liquids in it, but apparently the vibration from the truck caused some condensed moisture in the dust to settle to the bottom of the truck trailer and collect near the tailgate. Normally gaskets on the trailer’s tailgate would prevent any liquids from leaking from the trailer. However, once the tailgate was open for inspection, it was observed that a piece of plastic liner that is placed in the bottom of the trailer to aid with removal of the EAF dust from the trailer at the disposal site had become wrinkled and lodged between the gasket of the trailer bed and the gasket on the trailer tailgate. This small gap allowed the collected free liquids to leak from the trailer past the gaskets.    Corrective Action:  In addition to the absorbent material placed in the trailer, the wrinkled plastic was folded up out of the gasket’s pathway and attached with a peg to the plastic above it to ensure it did not fall between the gaskets upon closing the tailgate. The tailgate was closed and a proper seal of the gaskets was visually ensured

column168: OUR SEMI-TRACTOR TRAILER WAS HEADED EAST ON WYOMING HIGHWAY SR220 AT 06:00 ON JANUARY 12, 2006. A PICKUP TRUCK WAS HEADED WEST ON SR220. ROAD CONDITIONS WERE ICY. THE PICKUP SLID SIDEWAYS INTO OUR LANE OF  TRAFFIC. END RESULT WAS HEAD ON COLLISION AND JACK-KNIFE ACCIDENT INTO THE DITCH. TRAILER BROKE LOOSE  FROM UPPERCOUPLER AND ROLLED ON ITS SIDE. DRIVER OF THE PICKUP WAS A FATALITY. DRIVER OF THE SEMI REPORTED ACCIDENT TO DISPATCH VIA SATELLITE COMMUNICATION. TRANSWOOD THEN MOBILIZED EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAMS TO THE SIGHT. INITIAL RESPONDERS INDICATED A LEAK AT THE TRAILERS INTERNAL VALVE. THIS WAS NOT THE CASE, BUT MERELY CONDENSATION OF ICE & SNOW MELTING FROM THE VALVE TOP, AS CONFIRMED BY TESTING OF THE FLUIDS.     JANUARY 13 THE VEHICLES WERE UPRIGHTED AND REMOVED FROM THE ACCIDENT SITE. TRANSFER OF MATERIALS WAS DONE TO A TRAILER SUITABLE FOR HIGHWAY USE AND THE MATERIALS WERE DELIVERED IN THEIR ENTIRETY TO WHARF MINE IN LEAD, SD.     THE TRAILER SUSTAINED NO DAMAGE TO THE VESSEL, VALVES, OR ASSOCIATED PIPING, EXCLUDING AN AIR INLET PIPE THAT WAS BENT DURING THE ACCIDENT. EXTENT OF DAMAGES TO THE TRAILER WAS SUBFRAME, UNDERCARRIAGE, FENDER, AND STAINLESS INSULATION.

column168: At about 5:30 am on Sunday 1/15/06 a mobile acetylene trailer system (MATS) left 1-70 (eastbound) near milepost 136 in Columbia, MO, proceeded down an embankment and overturned, coming to rest against the bank of a small creek. A fire involving the MATS ensued and consumed the residual acetylene in the cylinders through fusible metal plugs that released acetylene from the cylinderrs, which remained with the trailer. The driver of the vehicle suffered fatal injuries although it is unclear whether a medical event occurred prior to the accident and contributed to the vehicle leaving the roadway.    The tractor trailer was driven by a team of drivers for Logex and was returning an empty residual acetylene trailer from a customer in Perry, Iowa to the Taft (Hahnville) acetylene trailer filling facility of Praxair Distribution Inc (“PDI”). The road is a long, straight road that has a slight downhill grade. Prior to mile post 136 on interstate 70 heading eastbound just east of Columbia, MO, the tractor trailer left the road where the road curves slightly to the left and has a slight downhill grade. The passenger tires left the right side of the roadway followed 105 later by the driver side wheels. There was no indication that the driver applied his brakes or attempted to turn for the curve. The second driver who was in the sleeper cab at the time the vehicle left the roadway stated that, he heard a noise and woke up to find that he was staring at the ground. He was able to free himself from the netting in the sleeper compartment and crawl free of the wreckage.

column168: Material Spill in Trailer:    On January 3, 2006 at approximately 16:00, Bob Kriegisch, Material Handler, was at B Dock unloading a North England Motor Freight (NEMF) trailer containing a shipment of 55-gallon drums from Ashland Distribution.  He was using a forklift with a Wesco® Drum Grab attached.  After successfully unloading a number of drums, the Drum Grab punctured the wall of a 55-gallon drum.  Bob did not see the puncture, but heard the splash as material spilled onto the bed of the trailer.  Bob called for Patrick Cope, Material Handler.  Patrick placed the damaged drum on a spill containment pallet and moved that drum/pallet outside.  Around the same time, Rick Burns, Jr., Process Specialist, happened upon the scene and provided assistance.  Around 16:30, Dave Lawson, Materials Planning Manager, and Norman Umberger, EHS Manager, was paged and responded to the scene.  An assessment of the situation was made and unloading/cleanup operations were halted.    Cleanup:    Rick initially entered the trailer without respiratory protection.  Norman identified the drum as containing ethyl acetate 99% (VE0022).  Norman collected information on ethyl acetate from the MSDS, the label, websites (EPA, NIOSH, OSHA, others), Ashland, Chemtrek, NEMF, and NIOSH pocket guide.  The primary hazard posed by Ethyl Acetate is flammability.  Ethyl Acetate evaporates rapidly which can accelerate the generation of an explosive atmosphere in closed spaces.  In addition, the vapor is heavier than air and can travel along the ground and accumulate in low points.    A toxic gas monitor was used to test the air inside the trailer and it was found to be above the 10% of the lower explosive limit (LEL), which is the level that OSHA considers potentially explosive.  At that time, cleanup operations were halted and the trailer was allowed to air out.    After determining how to clean up the spill, safely and effectively, Rick and Norm conducted the cleanup that day and into the next day.      Rick wore an SCBA when entering the trailer to take measurements with the toxic gas monitor and when moving, by hand, the drums around the trailer to allow for the ethyl acetate on the floor to evaporate.    Several spill control items—adsorbent “socks” and loose adsorbent—were used in the cleanup.  They were primarily to contain the material, that is prevent the ethyl acetate from leaving the trailer     Environmental Damage:    Environmental damage was minimal and was minimized through the swift actions of Rick, Bob, and Patrick.  The spill was contained within the facility and the trailer.  Approximately ten to twenty gallons were lost.  Ethyl Acetate has a low vapor pressure, so it all evaporated.    No hazardous material reached a waterway, sanitary sewer, storm sewer, or the ground.
column169: Internal Recommendations:    Package drums on pallets.  Status: Contacted Ashland and they agree to instruct loaders to palletize future shipments.    Exercise care at all times.  Status: Ongoing.  Spoke with all employees.    Obtain and organize additional Spill Kits across the facility according to typical potential hazards.  Status: Ordered and organized Spill Kits.

A NEW SEAL WAS INSTALLED TO THE BREADBOX COVER.  CAR WAS RELEASED WITH NO FURTHER DEFECTS.  CSX TRANSPORTATION HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGER, JIM BRISKI, SPOKE WITH SHIPPER REP. column62: Human Error; Improper Preparation for Transportation; Incorrectly Sized Component or Device
column168: 01/12/06 AT 04:50, CSX TRANSPORTATION RECEIVED A CALL FROM RICK KELLER, TRAIN MASTER, CUMBERLAND, MD., YARD, REPORTING A LEAK FROM A TANK CAR.  HE REPORTED THAT UTLX 666911 WAS LEAKING FROM SOMEWHERE AROUND THE TOP OF THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS LOCATED INSIDE THE CONFINES OF THE CUMBERLAND YARD.  UTLX666911, DOT 111A100W1 CONTAINING STYRENE MONOMER, STABILIZED CLASS 3 UN 2055 PGIII.  CSX TRANSPORTATION DISPATCHED SPSI (SPECIALIZED PROFESSIONAL SERVICES), CARY COWDEN (877-228-7774), CSX HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGER, S. MICHAEL AUSTIN (410-525-8233), ALONG WITH THE MARYLAND DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENT.  THE ALLEGANY HAZ-MAT TEAM WAS ON SITE AND REPORTED NO ACTIVE LEAK.  APPROXIMATE 4FT SPRAY OF PRODUCT WAS DRY ON BOTH SIDES OF THE CAR.  FURTHER INSPECTION FOUND A 4 BOLT BLIND FLANGE WAS BOLTED TO THE COVER PLATE NEXT TO THE LIQUID/VAPOR LINE.  THE BLIND FLANGE HAD BEEN TIGHTENED DOWN FLUSH WITH THE COVER PLATE ON ONE SIDE AND NOT THE OTHER.  A 2" TEFLON GASKET WITH THE NUMBER 044444-60 WAS USED.  SPSI REPLACED THE GASKET WITH A 4 BOLT TEFLON STYLE GASKET.  ONCE OF THE GASKET WAS REPLACED, CSX TRANSPORTATION MOVED THE CAR TO ENSURE THAT THE PROBLEM HAD BEEN RESOLVED.  AFTER THE CAR WAS MOVED, SPSI ALONG WITH CSX HAZ-MAT MANAGER, INSPECTED THE CAR.  NO LEAKS FOUND.  CAR WAS RELEASED WITH NO FURTHER DEFECTS.  CSX TRANSPORTATION HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SUPPORT DESK (ED COOK) SPOKE WITH JIM VONDRACEK AND BOB DONAVAN (412-778-6284) FROM ASHLAND CHEMICAL.

ON 01/12/06 AT 1630 HRS., MECHANICAL FORCES IN THE QUEENSGATE YARD FOUND TANK CAR GATX 12456 LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET.  AFTER INSTRUCTIONS FROM THE HAZ MAT MANAGER ON DUTY, CAR FOREMAN, GARY FREY, INSPECTED THE RAIL CAR AND WAS INSTRUCTED TO CHECK THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE TO SEE IF IT IS TIGHT.  TOBO VALVE WAS TURNED 3/4 OF A TURN TO STOP THE LEAK AT THE BOTTOM OUTLET ON THE CAR.  THE PACKING GLAND NUT WAS CLOSED 2 FULL TURNS TO TIGHTEN THE PACKING NUT.  THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WAS SECURED WITH A 36" PIPE WRENCH.  ALL LEAK STOPPED.  CHEMTREC NOTIFIED AT 1727, REPORT #01122006081.  RAIL CAR WAS FORWARDED.

column42: AEROSOLS, FLAMMABLE, (EACH NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY)
column168: FILE-06-6 FAA & DOT SHIPPER-FAIRCHILD PUBLICATIONS AWB#-JRA 39646900941 HTS  ON 01/08/2006 AT 1545, A LEAKING AND ODOROUS SHIPMENT WAS REPORTED IN "D" BUILDING OF OUR MAIN SORT FACILITY, LOCATED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177.  SPILL TECHNICIANS ELWOOD BOHL AND KENNETH OPPY DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL, THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE AND EMITTING AN ODOR.  THEY REMOVED THE PACKAGE FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION.  UPON THIS INVESTIGATION, THEY FOUND THIS PACKAGE TO CONTAIN MULTIPLE PERSONAL EFFECTS INCLUDING, 6 AEROSOL CANS MARKED FLAMMABLE, 9 AEROSOL CANS MARKED CONTENTS UNDER PRESSURE, NON-FLAMMABLE, 41 AEROSOL CANS MARKED FLAMMABLE, 9 AEROSOL CANS MARKED CONTENTS UNDER PRESSURE, NON-FLAMMABLE, 41 AEROSOL CANS MARKED FLAMMABLE, AND 3 BOTTLES MARKED FLAMMABLE.  DUE TO MISSING CLOSURES FROM 6 AEROSOL CANS, 46.5 OZ OF THE PRODUCT WAS LOST.  THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED INTO WILMINGTON VIA FLIGHT # 441, N767AX.  THIS INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO THE GREAT LAKES REGION FEDERAL AVIATION ADMINISTRATION.  THIS SHIPMENT DID HAVE MARKINGS/LABELS OR A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING IT TO INDICATE THAT THIS WAS A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  CLEAR OF SCENE: 1603.  THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE IN THE HAZMAT OFFICE IN WILMINGTON, OHIO.

column62: Human Error; Conveyer or Material Handling Equipment Mishap
column168: Apprx 1805, Friday, 1/06/2006 I received a call that a tank that had been loaded in cell 04, slot 82 bay 13 had been damaged on the ship and was leaking. Operator for tank UTCU45O1 290 is APL, booking 503133963, Shipper Stolt Nielsen % Celanese booked on the SL Motivator. Commodity Combustible Liquid Nos (Nonanol), NA 1993, PG III, Flash point 74C, 5740 gallons, 39560lbs  POHA Fire Department responded immediately. I notified M&M Protection Services our Emergency Response Vendor.  The crane operator had loaded all 2Oft containers on the forward end of hatch 4, including UTCU45O1 290. The crane moved back to load the aft end port to starboard While loading box 5 SAMU21 86477, the corner of the box came in contact with the valve on the tank causing itto leak.SAMU2186477 SAMU container was not damaged.  The tank was lifted off the vessel. Sonny Moody the walking foreman advised everyone in that area of hatch 4 to get off the dock and away from under the crane. POHA put absorbent down on the dock under the crane and land side. This assisted in absorbing the odor. The tank was placed on the dock on CS apprx. between 5200-5300 marker on the landside behind the crane legs. The area under the crane was opened apprx. 2030 hrs up for traffic movement but no employees were allowed to work hatch 4 as it had to be cleaned. The area from row 5 Z to the crane leg was shut off to traffic Friday night. We continued to work in hatch 8 apprx. 200 ft away.  Five flatbeds were stacked and the tank was leaned up against the flatbeds at a 45 degree angle using the Paceco crane. The tank was secured with chains to the flatbed.  A popup pool was placed on the top flat for the product to leak into. Absorbent was placed on the ground (concrete). Apprx 30 or less gallons leaked onto the dock.  Apprx 50 gallons leaked on the vessel. Most of the product was contained on the hatch cover. Some product had spilled on the walk ways. POHA Fire Depart and M&M representative conducted a inspection on the vessel. Sixteen containers had to be discharged off the vessel in order to clean off the hatch cover. The walking foreman unlashed the containers. He was supplied information regarding the product and a respirator. Absorbent pads were used to clean up the spill on the vessel. Two fire extinguishers were made available for use if needed. The chemical reacted with the pads. The pads were placed in drums. We used the water keg on the vessel at the gangway and pouired water in the drums to stop them from smoking. The product specialist advised when we completed the cleanup to put absorbent in the drums and pour copious amounts of water in the drum, which we did. We met with the chief mate on the vessel who approved the clean up. The tank was inspected and the nuts tightened again. The leak was down to a slow drip. The cool temperatures helped in keeping the product from expanding. We completed the cleanup appx. 3:30 a.m. on 1/7/05. There were six drums of clean up materials for disposaL

column168: ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT JON #22346:  ON JANUARY 3, 2006, THE UNIT WAS TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND ON HIGHWAY 151/61 AND WAS AT THE INTERSECTION OF HIGHWAY 151/61 AND TWIN VALLEY DRIVE NEAR DUBUQUE, IOWA WHEN THE TRAILER DISCONNECTED FROM THE TRACTOR UNIT.  THE TRAILER TRAVELED ACROSS THE ITNERSECTION AND CAME TO REST IN A DRAINAGE DITCH ON THE SOUTHWEST CORNER OF THE INTERSECTION.  THE UNIT REMAINED UPRIGHT.  THE TRAILER UNIT CONTAINED DIFFERENT TYPES OF FREIGHT TO INCLUDE SIX 55-GALLON DRUMS OF FLAMMABLE INL PRODUCTS.  THERE WERE FOUR (4) DRUMS OF ROTOFLEX PAPER OPV RE2 AND TWO (2) DRUMS OF FLEXO LAMIALL II CARBAZOLE VIOLET.  THE DUBUQUE COUNTY SHERIFF DEPARTMENT, THE DUBUQUE FIRE DEPARTMENT, AND THE IOWA DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION RESPONDED OT THE ACCIDENT SITE (NOTIFIED AT APPROXIMATELY 2245 HOURS).  THE DUBUQUE COUNTY SHERIFF DEPARTMENT NOTIFIED THE IOWA DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL RESOURCES AT APPROXIMATELY 0037 HOURS ON JANUARY4, 2006.  MICHELLE SMITH OF THE IOWA DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL RESOURCES RESPONDED TO THE SITE.  THE INCIDENT NUMBER GIVEN BY THE IOWA DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL RESOURCES WAS #010406-MAS-0037.  FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL MADE ENTRY INTO THE TRAILER.  IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE DRUM OF THE ROTOFLEX PAPER OPV RE2 HAD BEEN RUPTURED AND LOST ITS ENTIRE CONTENTS.  THE RELEASE HAD IMPACTED THE ENTIRE TRAILER FLOOR.  THE OTHER FIVE DRIMS HAD BEEN DAMAGED BUT WERE NOT LEAKING.   FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL PLACED ALL SIX (6) DRUMS INTO OVERPACK DRUMS.  APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS OF PRODUCT HAD LEAKED OUT THE FRONT CORNER OF THE TRAILER AND IMPACTED THE DRAINAGE DITCH WHICH HAD STANDING WATER.    MR. BELTRAN OF ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT HAD DISPATCHED SENECA ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (SES) TO THE INCIDENT.  SES PERSONNLE ARRIVED ON SITE AND BEGAN CLEANUP OERATIONS.  THE PRODUCT FROM THE DRAINAGE DITCH WAS RECOVERED.  THE IMPACTED SOI (15 FT. WIDE BY 100 FT LONG) WAS EXCAVATED AND PLACED INTO (3) 55-GALLON DRUMS.  ABSORBENTS WERE PLACED ON OTHER IMPACTED AREAS AND RECOVERED.  THESE MATERIAL WAS THEN MOVED TO WENZEL TOWING.  RESPONSE TEAM MEMBERS THEN COMPLETED THE CLEANUP OF THE TRAILER.  ALL WASTE DRUMS WERE TRANSPORTED TO THE LAKEVILLE MOTOR EXPRESS FACILITY IN ROCK ISLAND, ILLINOIS PENDING DISPOSAL ARRANGEMENT.

column168: CSXU 981155 NOTICED LEAKING BY DELIVERY DRAYMAN AT CSXI, TAMPA, FL INTERMODAL FACILITY.  HAZMAT SHIPMENT OF POLYMERIC BEADS, EXPANDABLE, CLASS 9, UN 2211, PG III.  SHIPMENT LOADED WITH 20 BAGS THAT MEASURE APPROX 4'X4'X4'.  BEADS ARE LEAKING WHERE THE CONTAINER FLOORING AND CONTAINER WALL CONNECTS AND SPILLED ONTO THE GROUND. BAG IS ONE HALF EMPTY.  A HOLE WAS FOUND APPROX ONE-QUARTER FROM THE BOTTOM OF BAG.  THERE WAS CARDBOARD AROUND WALLS OF CONTAINER TO PROTECT BAGS.  SWS CLEANED UP GROUND AND PLACED BEADS IN OVER-PACK DRUM AND PLACED DRUM INTO CONTAINER.  CONFIRMED WITH HUNTSMAN/ACTUAL SHIPPER & ROMAR/RAIL SHIPPER THAT UNLOADING ENTIRE SHIPMENT WOULD BE LENGTHY.  SHIPMENT HAS CLOSE DELIVERY DESTINATION THEREFORE, WAS AGREED TO TAPE CREVICES AND THEN DIAPER SHIPMENT FOR DELIVERY.  SWS WOULD THEN ESCORT AND TRAVEL BEHIND SHIPMENT TO DESTINATION.  HUNTSMAN HAD CONTACTED THE DELIVERY FACILITY AND MADE THEM AWARE OF THE SITUATION AND THEY ARE READY FOR THIS "AS IS" SHIPMENT.  CONTAINER WAS DELIVERED WITHOUT PRODUCT LEAKING.  RAR REPORT #000020098

MEANWHILE SHIPMENT WAS AT RAIL DESTINATION (CSXI WORCESTER, MA) AND UPS CHECKED THE SEALED POUCH ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE RAIL TRAILER. UPS PLACES THE HAZMAT SHIPPING PAPERS IN THIS SEALED PUCH AND IT REPRESENTS WHAT IS LOADED INTO TRAILER. THE PUCH CONTAINED ONE HAZMAT "COMPRESSED GAS, FLAMMABLE NOS (ISOBUTANE PROPANE) CLASS 21 UN 1954 WHICH WAS UNDECLARED TO CSXI. THIS COMMODITY WAS NOT THE SAME AS INDICATED BY THE UPS SHIPPING PAPER RECEIVED FROM BNSF. CSXI NEEDED CLARIFICATION- IF BOTH COMMODITIES ARE WITHIN SHIPMENT OR NOT. IN ORDER TO CONFIRM UPS CHECKED THE INSIDE OF THE TRAILER AND FOUND TWO HAZMAT'S INSIDE- COMPRESSED GAS, FLAMMABLE NOS ( ISOBUTANE PROPANE) CLASS 21 UN 1954 AND ISOPROPANOL, CLASS 3, UN 1219, PG II. THE AMINES, LIQUID CORROSIVE, NOS WAS OFFERED BY BNSF WITH A UPS SHIPPING PAPER BUT, WAS NOT FOUND TO BE IN SHIPMENT.    THEREFORE THE TWO UNDECLARED HAZMATS WERE COMPRESSED GAS, FLAMMABLE, NOS (ISOBUTANE PROPANE), CLASS 2.1 UN 1954 (IN POUCH BUT, NOT DECLARED) AND ISOPROPANOL, CLASS 3, UN 1219, PG II (NOT IN PUCH) AND NOT DECLARED TO CSXI. RAR REPORT #R000020140

I ALBERT RABANAL (DESIGNATED RESPONDER, RESPONDED TO A HAZMAT SPILL BY THE UNLOAD SUPERVISOR.  I WAS TOLD THAT THE PACKAGE WAS FUMING.  I IMMEDIATELY PUT ON PPE AND SCBA.  WHEN I GOT TO THE SPILL, I READ THE LABELS AND FOLLOWED THE DECISION TREE.  I DISCOVERED THE CONTENTS TO BE HYDROCHLORIC ACID, CORROSIVE #8.  I DID A PH TEST AND FOUND THE LIQUID TO BE ACIDIC.  I THEN POURED SODIUM BICARBONATE TO NEUTRALIZE THE ACID.  INCONCLUSION I CLEANED UP THE SPILL AND PROCESSED THE CONTENTS THROUGH DMP.

column168: AT 0847NHRS ON 1-7-06, FRANK LERCH, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED THAT MANAGER OF YARD OPERATIONS BOBBY ODEM, JR. REPORTED TANK CAR GATX 82369 LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR WHILE SWITCHING.  CAR HAD BEEN ISOLATED FOR FURTHER HANDLING.    WHILE ENROUTE, MGR LERCH, ADVISED THE RMCC TO MAKE SHIPPER NOTIFICATION VIA CHEM-TREC.  ON ARRIVAL, MGR LERCH NOTED THE SIDES OF THE CAR TO BE SLIGHTLY WET FROM PRODUCT, BUT OBSERVED THE PRODUCT TO BE DRYING.  INSPECITION OF THE CAR REVEALED THE MANWAY COVER GASKET WAS MISSING.  MGR LERCH FASHIONED A GASKET FROM GORTEX, PLACED IT ONTHE MANY, CLOSED THE MANWAY COVER, AND PROPERLY TIGHTENED ALL MANWAY SWINGBOLTS, WHICH SECURED THE CAR FOR TRANSPORATION.  MGR LERCH WIPED SIDES OF CAR, AND RELEASED IT TO CONTINUE ONTO DESITINATION WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.    AT 1130HRS, MGR LERCH SPOKE TO TRACEY THOMASEE, MGR OF SAFETY & LOGISTICS FOR KMTEX, AND ADVISED HIM OF THE NOTED EXCEPTIONS, AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TAKEN.    THERE WERE NO DRAINS, WATERWAYS, OR REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FORM THIS RELASE.    ORIGINAL MANWAY SEAL:  KMTEX-06433, REPLACED WITH UPRR CTS-08796.

column168: AT 2354HRS ON 1/10/06, FRANK LERCH, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS CONTACTED BY THE RMCC AND ADVISED THAT JAYSON JENKINS, MANAGER OF YARD OPERATIONS HAD REPORTED TANK CAR UTLX 802791 WAS VENTING.  CAR WAS LOCATED IN TRACK 2, DAYTON, TX.  ON ARRIVAL AND INSPECTION OF CAR, MGR. LERCH NOTED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM B END, BOTTOM SIDE OF THE TANK CAR OVER THE TRUCK ASSEMBLY.  PRODUCT WAS ESTIMATED TO BE LEAKING AT A RATE OF 1 GALLON EVERY 10 MINUTES, WITH A SLIGHT PRODUCT CLOUD TRAVELING SOUTH FROM THE CAR CROSSING OVER HWY 90.  MGR. LERCH REQUESTED THE RMCC CONTACT THE DAYTON POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENT REQUESTING HWY 90 BE CLOSED DOWN TO ALL VEHICLE TRAFFIC.  MGR.LERCH THEN REQUESTED THE RMCC MAKE SHIPPER NOTIFICATION VIA CHEM-TREC.  AFTER INITIAL NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE, MRG. LERCH CONTACTED THE CENTER FOR TOXICOLOGY AND ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH AND REQUESTED A TEAM BE DISPATCHED TO CONDUCT. PREPAREDNESS FOR BAYER AND ADVISED HIM OF THE CONDITION OF THE CAR AND ACTIONS TAKEN. MR. BURKET THEN ADVISED THAT HE AND A RESPONSE TEAM WOULD BE RESPONDING.  REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, TIM OB BRIEN & ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR CORY ANDERSON OF UNITED STATES ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES ALSO RESPONDED.  AT 0320HRS MGR. LERCH WITH THE ASSISTANCE OF MR. ANDERSON SECURED A MAGNETIC PATCH OVER THE SOURCE OF THE RELEASE WHICH STOPPED THE CAR FOR FURTHER LEAKAGE.  AT 0450HRS CAR UTLX 802791 WAS MOVED TO A SET-OUT TRACK FOR OFF LOADING OF PRODUCT INTO TRUCKS.  AFTER SECURING THE CAR, AND CONDUCTING AIR MONITORING, AT 0502HRS HWY 90 WAS APPROXIMATELY 0600HRS CTEH PERSONNEL ARRIVED ON SITE, AND CONDUCTED REAL TIME AIR MONITORING FOR THE AREA AND THROUGHOUT THE TRANSFER OPERATION.  AT 12:05HRS OFF LOADING OF THE CAR BEGAN BY CONTRACTED PERSONNEL FROM REAGENT CHEMICAL & RESEARCH, INC.  FOUR TANK TRUCKS WERE USED TO OFF LOAD THE PRODUCT WHICH WAS TAKEN BACK TO BAYER IN BAYTOWN, TX.  AT 1614HRS THE TRANSFER WAS COMPLETE WITH ALL PRODUCT REMOVED FROM THE TANK CAR.  UPON COMPLETION OF THE TRANSFER, THE CAR WAS MARKED SHOP FOR REPAIRS, DO NOT LOAD, LEAKING TANK.  THE CAR WAS THEN BILLED TO A REPAIR SHOP MOVING UNDER FRA MOVEMENT APPROVAL #06010025 FOR NECESSARY REPAIRS.  CAUSE OF THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A FAILED LINER APPROXMATELY 30 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS ESTIMATED TO HAVE LEAKED FROM THE CAR WITH NO DRAINS OF WATERWAYS AFFECTED.  TWO EMPLOYEES COMPLAINED OF EXPOSURE, AND WERE TAKEN TO A LOCAL HOSPITAL WERE THEY WERE TREATED FOR INHALATION AND THROAT IRRITATION.

AT 0950HRS KELLY ARRIVED ON SCENE AND REPLACED THE O RINGS ON THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE. column168: UPRRS RESPONSE MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATIONS CENTER NOTIFIED LANE SEKAVEC, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION  SAFETY OF A REPORTED CHLORINE ODOR FROM A TANK CAR AT 18TH STREET YARD, KANSAS CITY, KS.  HUNTER BLACKWELL, MYO, ADVISED EMPLOYEES COULD SMELL CHLORINE IN THE AREA OF HOKX 7848.  MR. SAKAVEC PROCEEDED TO THE YARD AND EXAMINED THE TANK CAR FROM THE GROUND, DETECTING A MINOR ODOR OF CHLORINE.  A CHLORINE GASTEC TUBE WAS USED TO QUANTIFY THE AMOUNT OF RELEASE AND A READING OF LESS THAN .5 PARTS PER MILLION WAS REGISTERED AT THE GROUND.  DUE TO AN INJURY, MR  SEKAVAC WAS UNABLE TO CLIMB THE TANK CAR TO DO AN EVALUATION. RMCC CONTACTED CHEMTREC AND TERRY SPENCER WITH BASIC CHEMICAL 9SHIPPER) CONTACTED MR. SEKAVEC AND ADVISED A RESPONSE TEAM FROM THE PLANT IN WICHITA WOULD RESPOND AND EVALUATE/REPAIR THE TANK CAR.  WHEN THE BASIC ARRIVED, EVALUATION  OF THE TANK CARE REVEALED THAT THE B-END LIQUID VALVE WAS SLIGHTLY OPEN AND THE PLUG WAS ABLE TO BE TIGHTENED SLIGHTLY AS WELL. THE VALVE AND PLUG WERE SECURED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE IN TRANSPORTATION.  NO REMEDIATION WAS NEEDED FOR THIS RELEASE AS IT WAS VAPOR ONLY FORM THE VALVE.  READINGS ON THE CHLORINE METER USED BY THE BASIC TEAM PRIOR TO SECURING THE VALVE WERE BETWEEN.5 AND 1 PART PER MILLION ON THE TOP OF THE TANK CAR.

column168: ACCIDENT 12-12:15 PM 1/6/2005.  724 HANCOCK STREET, ABINGTON.  ICE ROAD CONDITION.  WOMAN COMING SOUTH ON HANCOCK.  JIM TEMPESTA DRIVING NORTH AT 15-20 MPH.  SPEED LIMIT ON ROAD IS 30-35 MPH.  JIM SAW OV FISH TAILING DOR ABOUT 1/4 MILE - MOVED ONTO A YARD ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE ROAD AND TOOK DOWN MAILBOX.  ONE HALF VEHICLE WAS ON THE YARD.  OV HIT IV AT ABOUT 40 OR 50 MPH SPINNING OIL TRUCK ABOUT 180 DEGRESS.  TURCK THEN FLIPPED OVER.  FIRE CHIEF MADE STATEMENT SAYING IT WAS WOMAN'S FAULT ON THE NEWS.  JIM CHECKED ON WOMAN IN OV. JIM WAS HELPED OUT BY 2 PEOPLE THAT LIVED ON THE STREET.  ONCE JIM WAS OUT HE CHECKED IN THE WOMAN.  WOMAN WAS LYING ON THE SEAT OF THE CAR AND WAS MOVING.  FIRE DEPT. WAS IN THE STREET AND RESPONDED WITHIN 5 MINUTES.  DOT WAS ON SCENE WITHIN 5-10 MIN. JIM WAS SENT OVER TO PICK-UP TRUCK FOR ABOUT 1/2 HR.  TWO AMBULANCES FOR THE ACCIDENT.  EMT ATTENDED TO WOMAN AND TAKEN TO HOSPITAL.  TOOK JIM'S NAME AND INFO PERSON ON-SITE.  APPROX. 1 HOUR AFTER ACCIDENT 2 MECHANICS CAME ONSITE AND 7:00PM TRUCK WAS REMOVED FROM SCENE - TOWED TO LYONS TOWING IN BROCKTON.  FIRE DEPT. WAS SPREADING WATER ON SPILLED OIL.
